91
00:04:53,200 --> 00:04:55,760
some observable experiential fact.

92
00:04:55,760 --> 00:04:57,360
Now we're ready to state the puzzle.

93
00:04:57,360 --> 00:05:01,280
How can we have a theory of language, a theory of names,

94
00:05:01,280 --> 00:05:04,640
that explains these two features of sentence number two,

95
00:05:04,640 --> 00:05:06,480
that it can be informative,

96
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:08,720
and then more specifically, the kind of information

97
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:12,240
that it can give can be empirical information.

98
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:16,640
The reason this is a puzzle is that there was this other theory

99
00:05:16,640 --> 00:05:20,720
of names published in 1881 by John Stuart Mill

100
00:05:20,720 --> 00:05:22,480
and according to Mill's theory,

101
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:26,480
the meaning of a proper name like Sean Carter or Jay-Z,

102
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:28,880
the meaning of a name like that is nothing more

103
00:05:28,880 --> 00:05:30,320
than the object named.

104
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:32,560
And Mill's theory sounds really good

105
00:05:32,560 --> 00:05:35,280
when you read that paper that he published in 1881,

106
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:37,280
but then you run into cases like this

107
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:38,480
and he can't handle this.

108
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:40,480
According to Mill, the name Sean Carter

109
00:05:40,480 --> 00:05:43,600
and the name Jay-Z mean exactly the same thing.

110
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:46,240
And so sentence one and sentence two are no different.

111
00:05:46,240 --> 00:05:49,360
Mill is unable to explain why a sentence like two

112
00:05:49,360 --> 00:05:52,160
can be genuinely illuminating, informative,

113
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:54,240
why it can have some cognitive value

114
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:56,000
in a way that a sentence like one doesn't.

115
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,320
Because after all, on Mill's theory,

116
00:05:58,320 --> 00:06:01,520
the meaning of these letters right here is just the dude

117
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:03,280
and the meaning of these letters right here

118
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:04,480
is the exact same dude.

119
00:06:04,480 --> 00:06:07,680
So it's just this dude is this dude.

120
00:06:07,680 --> 00:06:11,360
Yeah, duh, just like in this case, this dude is this dude.

121
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:12,320
There's no difference.

122
00:06:12,320 --> 00:06:14,720
Now there's an alternative to Mill's theory

123
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:17,600
that can explain how sentence two

124
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:20,400
can be illuminating, informative,

125
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:22,160
in a way that sentence one can't.

126
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:25,680
And that theory translates sentence two

127
00:06:25,680 --> 00:06:28,880
as a sentence about language itself.

128
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:34,000
On this theory, sentence two is really just shorthand

129
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,240
for something like sentence two star.

130
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:41,120
The name Sean Carter and the name Jay-Z denote the same person.

131
00:06:41,120 --> 00:06:42,560
If this is what two means,

132
00:06:42,560 --> 00:06:45,840
then it makes sense why two is informative

133
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:47,200
in a way that one isn't.

134
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:49,440
One would be translated correspondingly

135
00:06:49,440 --> 00:06:51,360
as something like the name Sean Carter

136
00:06:51,360 --> 00:06:54,320
and the name Sean Carter denote the same person.

137
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:55,280
That's obvious.

138
00:06:55,280 --> 00:06:56,560
But this is not obvious.

139
00:06:56,560 --> 00:06:59,040
Like this is a fact that you might not know.

140
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:03,120
And this theory that translates identity statements like this

141
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:05,600
into sort of linguistic statements like this,

142
00:07:05,600 --> 00:07:08,560
that theory is actually Fraga's old theory

143
00:07:08,560 --> 00:07:12,080
from the Begriff Schrift, which he published in 1879.

144
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:17,840
But 13 years went by between 1879 and 1892

145
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:19,760
when he published On Sense and Reference.

146
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:23,520
And during those 13 years, Fraga realized that this theory,

147
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:25,600
the theory that translates identity statements

148
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:27,760
into linguistic statements like this,

149
00:07:27,760 --> 00:07:29,360
that theory wasn't good.

150
00:07:29,360 --> 00:07:32,960
And the reason is that statements like number two here

151
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:35,360
can be informative, not just informative,

152
00:07:35,360 --> 00:07:37,040
but empirically informative.

153
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:40,080
The idea is simply that when Ellen had this moment

154
00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:41,680
of realization on the subway,

155
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:44,560
she wasn't realizing something about the meanings

156
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:47,040
of these terms, she was realizing something

157
00:07:47,040 --> 00:07:48,320
about the world around her.

158
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:49,280
And Fraga gets this.

159
00:07:49,280 --> 00:07:51,920
He understands all this stuff about Ellen and Jay-Z.

160
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:54,320
And so what he does in On Sense and Reference

161
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:56,640
is he tosses out his old theory

162
00:07:56,640 --> 00:07:59,200
and he gives a new theory of sentences like that.

163
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:02,640
And it turns out to be not just a theory of identity statements

164
00:08:02,640 --> 00:08:04,640
like this, but of all of language.

165
00:08:06,160 --> 00:08:08,240
Very quickly, I'm going to illustrate this again

166
00:08:08,240 --> 00:08:09,760
with Fraga's own example,

167
00:08:09,760 --> 00:08:13,040
which involves the morning star and the evening star.

168
00:08:13,040 --> 00:08:13,680
To understand this,

169
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:16,880
you're going to need some astronomical background information.

170
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:17,760
So here it is.

171
00:08:17,760 --> 00:08:21,440
If you look at the sunrise, just before sunrise,

172
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:24,480
right near where the sun is about to rise,

